5000|$|An {{embedded}} <b>democracy</b> can <b>be</b> {{considered a}} type of consolidated democracy, meaning that the democratic regime in an embedded <b>democracy</b> <b>is</b> seen as legitimate and stable. Political scientists debate the definition of democratic consolidation, but at minimum, a consolidated <b>democracy</b> <b>is</b> entrenched so that <b>democracy</b> <b>is</b> considered [...] "the only game in town." [...] Some scholars, like Merkel, take a maximalist approach to defining consolidated democracy by specifying the partial regimes of consolidation. Gunther considers three dimensions of consolidation—institutional, attitudinal, and behavioral—while Linz and Stepan highlight five arenas for consolidation: civil society, political society, rule of law, the state apparatus and economic society.|$|R
